<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-580-805  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 580 805.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Wall Street Journal  Nov 9 1990 pR45(W) pR38(E) 44 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Motorola on the move; the company is pushing a 77-satellitecellular system that would serve remote areas around the world.andO;(Technology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rose, Robert L.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Motorola Inc pushes a 77-satellite cellular system that allowsusers to connect with callers from around the world.andP;  Motorolaseeks foreign investors to help develop this wirelesscommunications system and foreign government licenses to controlthe frequencies these low-orbiting satellites will use.andP;  Theestimated cost to consumers will be $3,000 for a telephone, $50 amonth charge and $3 a minute to use.andP;  Motorola plans to have twodemonstration satellites launched by 1992 and the entire77-satellite system in place by 1996.andP;  The system will allowpeople to be reached in faraway and remote places, such as desertsand the high seas, with the use of Iridium where local,ground-based cellular systems and telephone lines are notavailable.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Motorola Inc. (Planning).andO;Ticker:    MOT.andO;Topic:     Communications IndustrySatellite CommunicationsTrends.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>